548–1625","1511–1557":"1511–1557","21 July 1548":"21 July 1548","July 1557":"July 1557","1592":"1592","27 January 1533":"27 January 1533","1535":"1535","1557":"1557","1545":"1545","1600":"1600","1511":"1511","1540":"1540","1507":"1507","about 1540":"about 1540","1549":"1549","1548":"1548","1625":"1625","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Speed","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>sped</i> ‘success, prosperity, wealth, smooth progress’ (hence the modern meaning ‘swiftness’); also ‘speed, quickness’ (Old English <i>sped</i>), used either for a fortunate, wealthy, or successful person, or for a swift runner.","Irish (Mayo): when not the English name, adopted for Gaelic <b>Ó Fuada</b>, from <i>fuad</i> ‘haste’ (see   Foody  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Schnell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Spieth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Erwin, Hannes, Helmut, Kurt, Manfred, Otto.","German:","nickname from Middle High German <i>spuot</i> ‘successful, speedy’. Compare   Speed  ."]},{"name":"Foody","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Siobhan.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Fuada</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Fuada</i>’, a personal name from <i>fuad</i> ‘haste’. Compare   Rush  ,   Speed  , and   Swift  . Occasionally written as <b>Ó hUada</b>, see   Huddy  ."]},{"name":"Speedy","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>spedi</i> ‘fortunate, successful, swift’ (compare   Speed  )."]},{"name":"Spedding","meanings":["English (northern): nickname from Middle English <i>speding</i> ‘success, achievement’, a derivative of the verb <i>speden</i> ‘to succeed’, perhaps used to refer to a successful person. See also   Speed  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":38,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Speed was born in 1511, in Great Bromley, Essex, England. She married Simon Stone on 27 January 1533, in Great Bromley, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in July 1557, in her hometown, at the age of 46, and was buried in Great Bromley, Essex, England."},"et":{"1511–July 1557":"1511–juuli 1557","1507–1557":"1507–1557","1535–1592":"1535–1592","1540–1625":"1540–1625","1545–1600":"1545–1600","1548–1625":"1548–1625","1511–1557":"1511–1557","21 July 1548":"21. juuli 1548","July 1557":"juuli 1557","1592":"1592","27 January 1533":"